  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>Most apartments, townhouses, and units in Brisbane are sold within a community title scheme. Unlike the strata title system used in New South Wales and Victoria, Queensland regulates these properties under the Body Corporate and Community Management Act 1997, which creates a distinct legal framework with its own terminology, disclosure requirements, and management structures. For sellers, understanding the framework is not optional: your contract of sale must include specific community title information, and a failure to disclose accurately can expose you to legal consequences after settlement.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What a community title scheme actually is</h2>
      <p>A community title scheme is the legal structure that governs a property where individual lots (your apartment or townhouse) are sold alongside shared ownership of common property (gardens, driveways, lobbies, pools, lifts). The scheme is managed by a body corporate, which is made up of all lot owners and is responsible for maintaining the common property, setting and collecting levies, and enforcing the community management statement and by-laws that govern how the scheme operates.</p>

      <p>This is substantively similar to strata in New South Wales, but the specific rules, terminology, and regulatory oversight differ. Queensland uses the term "body corporate" rather than "owners corporation," and the community management statement rather than a strata scheme management statement. If you have previously sold or purchased in another state, be aware that Queensland's community title requirements are specific to this jurisdiction and you should not assume the same documents, processes, or obligations apply.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The community management statement and by-laws</h2>
      <p>The community management statement is a registered document that sets out the by-laws for the scheme, the lot entitlements for each lot, any rights of exclusive use over common property, and the dispute resolution arrangements. It is a public document registered with the Queensland Land Registry and is fundamental to understanding what owners can and cannot do within the scheme.</p>

      <p>By-laws can restrict a wide range of activities: keeping pets, short-term letting (including Airbnb), parking, renovation works, the type of window coverings permitted, and noise levels. They can also create obligations, such as maintaining your balcony garden to a specified standard or repairing fixtures that fall within your lot's maintenance responsibility. Buyers will scrutinise the by-laws carefully, and buyers who intend to let the property short-term or keep pets will specifically check whether the by-laws permit this before proceeding.</p>

      <p>As a seller, you do not need to summarise every by-law for your buyers. But you should be aware of any by-laws that are particularly restrictive or that depart from what buyers might reasonably expect, and you should be honest with your agent so that relevant by-laws can be raised with prospective buyers before they commit. A buyer who discovers a by-law that prevents their intended use after they have signed a contract is a buyer who will look for a way out of that contract.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What your disclosure obligations are as a seller</h2>
      <p>Queensland law requires that a contract for the sale of a lot in a community title scheme must include a disclosure statement that provides the buyer with specific information about the scheme. The disclosure statement must be attached to the contract before it is signed and must include the current levies (both administration fund and sinking fund contributions), any special levies that have been approved or are currently proposed, a copy of the community management statement, and a body corporate certificate confirming information about the scheme's financial position and any liabilities.</p>

      <p>If the disclosure statement contains a material inaccuracy (for example, if it understates the levies or fails to disclose an approved special levy), the buyer may have a right to terminate the contract. Getting the disclosure statement right is not optional and not something to leave to the last minute. Your solicitor or conveyancer will prepare this document, but you need to provide them with accurate information about current levies and any special levies that have been resolved or are in progress.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What a body corporate records search reveals</h2>
      <p>Almost every purchaser of a community title lot in Queensland will obtain a body corporate records search before settlement. This is a detailed inspection of the body corporate's records, conducted by a specialist search company, and it covers a wide range of information that is not contained in the disclosure statement or the community management statement alone.</p>

      <p>A records search typically reveals the body corporate's financial statements and levy contribution history, the minutes of recent annual general meetings and committee meetings (including any motions that were passed, deferred, or controversial), the status of the administration fund and sinking fund (whether they are adequately funded or running a deficit), any correspondence with lot owners about disputes or compliance issues, and the details of any current litigation, insurance claims, or significant maintenance works that have been approved or are under discussion.</p>

      <p>Buyers use this information to assess the financial health of the scheme, whether the levies are likely to increase significantly in the near term, whether there are known defects in the common property that are not yet resolved, and whether the body corporate is effectively managed. A records search that reveals a poorly funded sinking fund, a pending special levy for significant structural works, or a history of contested decision-making will give buyers cause for concern and may affect their offer price or their willingness to proceed at all.</p>

      <p>You cannot control what a records search reveals. But you can be honest with your agent about what is in your body corporate's records so that your marketing sets realistic expectations and your pricing reflects any negative factors that will be visible to buyers before settlement.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Lot entitlements, voting rights, and levy proportions</h2>
      <p>Each lot in a community title scheme is assigned a lot entitlement, which is a number expressed as a proportion of the total entitlements across the scheme. Lot entitlements serve two purposes: they determine each lot owner's contribution to the body corporate levies, and they determine each owner's voting power in certain body corporate decisions.</p>

      <p>In most schemes, larger lots with higher lot entitlements pay more in levies and have more influence in general meetings. This is a factor that sophisticated buyers will check, particularly in schemes with a small number of lots where individual owners' voting positions can significantly affect how the body corporate is run. As a seller, you should be able to tell prospective buyers what your current quarterly or annual levy contributions are, as this is information they will be asking for.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Common issues that affect sale price or delay settlements</h2>
      <p>The most common community title issues that affect property sales in Brisbane fall into a few categories. Underfunded sinking funds are a significant concern for buyers, because a scheme that has not adequately accumulated reserves for future capital works will either need a special levy or will defer necessary maintenance. Either outcome costs future owners money. If your scheme's sinking fund is below the level recommended in the most recent sinking fund forecast, expect buyers to factor this into their pricing.</p>

      <p>Approved or pending special levies are another common issue. A special levy is an additional contribution required of all lot owners to fund a specific expense, such as roof replacement, facade rectification, or common property upgrades. If a special levy has been approved by the body corporate but has not yet been paid in full, this must be disclosed to the buyer. Special levies are not always a dealbreaker, but they need to be handled clearly in the contract to avoid disputes about who is responsible for payment.</p>

      <p>By-law compliance issues, including unauthorised modifications to lots, are also a potential complication. If you have made alterations to your lot that were not formally approved by the body corporate, this may need to be regularised before or at settlement. Your solicitor can advise you on how to handle this.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">How to present a community title property to maximise buyer confidence</h2>
      <p>The best thing you can do as a seller of a community title property is be transparent and organised from the outset. Have your levy notices ready so buyers can see exactly what the current contributions are. Know whether any special levies have been approved or discussed at recent meetings. Have a copy of the community management statement available for buyers who want to review the by-laws. Be straightforward about the condition of the common property and any known works that are planned.</p>

      <p>Buyers who feel informed and confident about the body corporate are more likely to proceed decisively and less likely to use the records search period to renegotiate or withdraw. Uncertainty breeds hesitation, and hesitation in a property sale often means lost buyers. A well-presented community title property with a transparent, well-funded body corporate is a genuinely desirable asset for the right buyer, and presenting it that way gives your sale the best possible start.</p>

